    <subsubsection>
      <title>Determining Whether or Not a Rule is a Function</title>
      <p>
        Each of the following exercises describes a rule which could be used to process information.
        Determine whether or not the given rule is a function.
        Clearly justify your answer.
      </p>
      <exercises><exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>f</m> be the rule that names the biological father of each living human being.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Yes this is a function.
            Each input (living human being) has one and only one biological father.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>m</m> be the rule that gives the legal spouse of every legally married American.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>c</m> be the rule that assigns to each biological father his child.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            No, this is not a function.
            There are some inputs
            (biological fathers)
            who have more than one child.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>w</m> be the rule that assigns to each person who has ever gotten married the person they married.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>P</m> be the rule that determines the current selling price for each item in stock at the Macedon, NY Walmart store.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Yes, this is a function.
            Each item has one and only one price (when the cashier rings it up there is only one price that comes up.)
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>D</m> be the rule that determines the current selling price for each item in stock at a dollar store.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>g</m> be the rule that gives each student who completes this course his or her final course grade.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Yes, this is a function.
            Each input (student) gets only one final grade.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>k</m> be the rule that gives each student enrolled at this college his or her current grade point average.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>m</m> be the rule that assigns to each dog owner his or her dog.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            No, this is not a function.
            Some inputs
            (dog owners)
            have more than one output (dogs they own.)
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>n</m> be the rule that assigns to each owned dog its owner.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>f(x)=(x-3)(x+2)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Yes, this is a function.
            If you input any real number and evaluate the result,
            you get one and only one answer.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>g(x)=3x^2+1</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>g(t)=\frac{2t+1}{t-1}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Yes, this is a function.
            If you input any real number except <m>t=1</m>,
            you get one and only one answer. (<m>t=1</m> is not a problem because it is excluded from the domain,
            and even if you ignored this fact and input <m>t=1</m> you would give you no output,
            not more than one)
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>h(x)=\frac{x^2-1}{x-1}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>f(x)=0</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Yes, this is a function.
            No matter what you use as input,
            you get only one output (the output is always zero.)
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>c(t)=42</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercises></subsubsection>
