      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>f(x) = x^2</m> find two different input values which give the same output value.
            Does the fact that you can do this mean <m>f(x)</m> is not a function?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            There are many possible answers.
            Take any positive number and the corresponding negative number.
            <m>3</m> and <m>-3</m> for example,
            since <m>f(3)=3^2=9</m> and <m>f(-3)=(-3)^2=9</m>.
            This is not a problem,
            since it is fine for two different inputs to give the same output.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
